The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, May 07, 2004 				 Raymond net up 21% in fourth quarter
 OUR BUREAUX																								May 6: Raymond Ltd has recorded a 21 per cent growth in net profit for the fourth quarter ended March 31, 2004 at Rs 39.41 crore against Rs 32.44 crore in the year-ago period.																								In 2003-04, Raymond posted profit before tax and exceptional items at Rs 183.13 crore, up 39.59 per cent from Rs 131.19 crore posted the previous year.																								Net profit, after provision for prior year adjustments, income and wealth taxes, was higher by 46.48 per cent at Rs 132.29 crore (Rs 90.25 crore). 																								The gross turnover of the company increased 7.34 per cent at Rs 1,091.53 crore (Rs 1,016.87 crore).																								After appropriating Rs 2.50 crore (Rs 3.75 crore) to the debenture redemption reserve and Rs 60 crore (Rs 67 crore) to the general reserves, the board recommended an enhanced dividend of 55 per cent (45 per cent).																								Raymond said despite spiralling wool prices and difficult conditions in the international market, the sales of the textile division registered a growth of 6 per cent at Rs 721.38 crore (Rs 680.63 crore) and the profit of the division rose 13.31 per cent at Rs.121.70 crore (Rs 107.40 crore).Syndicate Bank net up																								Syndicate Bank has reported a net profit of Rs 434 crore in 2003-04, up 26.16 per cent over Rs 344 crore registered in the previous year. The banks total business grew by 34.81 per cent at Rs 64,390 crore in 2003-04 against Rs 47,687 crore in 2002-03, chairman and managing director Michael Bastian said.																								He said advances stood at Rs 21,705 crore, up by 27.48 per cent over Rs 17,026 crore in 2002-03. Of this, retail credit at Rs 5,631 crore constituted 30.59 per cent of the total domestic advances.BOC profit jumps																								BOC India Ltd has reported a 79.7 per cent rise in net profit for the fiscal ended March 31, 2004 at Rs 29.3 crore against Rs 16.3 crore posted in the previous year. 																								Turnover of the company grew to Rs 347.2 crore from Rs 322.3 crore in 2002-03, a release said. 
